The micromorphologies of MWCNTs, UiO-66, and UiO-66-CNTs were analyzed by SEM. From the SEM image (Fig. S1
                        ), MWCNT exhibited a coiled, intertwined tubular structure, and UiO-66 displayed high dispersion and uniform octahedral structure. For the UiO-66-CNTs (
                        Fig. 2A), it can be seen that a rough, staggered-wound tubular structure. Further, its local magnification profile (Fig. 2B) showed that the UiO-66 nanoparticles were uniformly grown on the surface of linear MWCNTs [28]. The EDS spectrum (Fig. 2C) shows the characteristic peaks of C, Zr, and O, which were the main constituent elements of the raw material used to synthesize UiO-66-CNTs. The UiO-66-CNTs composites were further analyzed by the FTIR spectra. In Fig. 2D, the spectra of UiO-66 showed the typical peaks of N-H stretching at 1655 cm−1, demonstrating the existence of -NH2 group [29]. Besides, the absorption peaks at 1381 cm−1 and 1570 cm−1 were attributed to the bending vibration of -CH from -CH2 and -CH3 and aromatic CC stretching vibration [30]. And the CC vibration on the benzene ring showed strong absorption peaks at 1433 cm −1. Compared with the pure UiO-66, the spectra of composites were relatively unchanged, while the strength of the peak increased. There were some small changes in the composites, this was caused by the introduction of functional groups brought with the surface of MWCNTs [31]. Moreover, the chemical environment of protons in the MWCNTs, UiO-66, and UiO-66-CNTs was probed using 1H NMR (Fig. S2). It is clearly seen that MWCNTs did not showed any peaks, UiO-66 displayed resonances at 7.95 and 8.32 ppm which are characteristic of the two distinct protons on the aromatic ring and the amino groups. The NMR profile of the UiO-66-CNTs was similar to UiO-66, but the peaks were shifted slightly, which may be mediated by UiO-66 and MWCNTs interactions.
